article.description: Three days after Deanna Nolan's buzzer-beating jumper beat them in Cleveland, the Rockers blew a lead in the final four minutes and lost to the Detroit Shock 74-71 at the Palace on Tuesday afternoon.
article.headline: Shock has won four in a row
article.linkText: Detroit shocks Cleveland for second time in days
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Cleveland Rockers aren't quite sure how they just lost two games to the Detroit Shock.

Three days after Deanna Nolan's buzzer-beating jumper beat them in Cleveland, the Rockers blew a lead in the final four minutes and lost 74-71 at the Palace on Tuesday afternoon.

"This is frustrating because we shouldn't have lost to them down there and we shouldn't have lost to them here," said LaToya Thomas, who led the Rockers with 17 points. "But that's a good team, and it isn't easy to pull these games out."

The win extended Detroit's winning streak to four games and increased its Eastern Conference lead to three games over Charlotte. The Shock and the Sting play Thursday afternoon in Charlotte.

"Our biggest goal is to finish first in the East and get home-court advantage," said Cheryl Ford, who had 14 points and 14 rebounds. "It's fun when you are winning games like this."

Ford's rookie season continues to impress her coach.

"She just keeps getting better," Bill Laimbeer said. "She's a monster on the boards, and she hit some clutch shots today. That was a veteran performance out there today."

Swin Cash and Ruth Riley also had 14 for Detroit, which had five players in double figures.

"With Swin Cash, Cheryl Ford and Ruth Riley, Detroit has a great front line," Thomas said. "That's why it is always so tough to beat them, especially in their own building."

Chasity Melvin added 15 points and nine rebounds for Cleveland.

Detroit led 39-34 at the half and expanded the margin to nine early in the second.

Cleveland, though, went on a 17-6 run to take the lead and had a 60-54 lead with 9:25 left.

Detroit came back to tie the score at 67-all on Ford's put-back with 2:56 left. A Ford jumper and a Cash free throw put the Shock up three, and after Melvin split a pair of free throws, two Cash layups seemed to put the game away.

But Melvin hit a 3-pointer to make it 74-71 and Elaine Powell missed two free throws to give Cleveland a last chance to tie.

Betty Lennox missed a long 3-pointer and Nolan won the ensuing jump ball to clinch the win. Cleveland finished with just two field goals in the last eight minutes.

"People don't talk about our defense, but if you look at the statistics, we are number one in the league across the board," Laimbeer said. "That's what we are hanging our hat on right now, and that's why we don't panic in close games."

NOTES: The game started at 11 a.m. as a promotion to bring in kids from day camps. ... Cleveland coach Dan Hughes and Thomas picked up first-half technicals for arguing calls. ... The Shock are 6-4 against Cleveland on the road but just 4-5 at home. ... Cleveland fell to sixth in the East, but the Rockers trail the Shock by just five games.
